{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638670"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:57:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:57:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17726"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17726"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.25,0.05,0.45,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10440"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72140"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10440"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17726"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57610"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10330"},{"type":"tags","id":"10331"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24382"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72140"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following brain changes is associated with chronic pain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased emotional processing","Reduced connectivity between frontal and insular cortex with subcortical structures","Increased grey matter volume in the prefrontal cortex","Enhanced sensory processing in the thalamus","Decreased activity in the amygdala"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic pain is associated with various changes in brain structure and function. One of the key changes is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduced connectivity between the frontal and insular cortex with subcortical structures\u003C/strong\u003E. This altered connectivity is thought to contribute to the persistence of pain and the emotional and cognitive aspects of chronic pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased emotional processing\u003C/strong\u003E is often observed in chronic pain, as the condition can lead to heightened emotional responses and altered mood. However, this is not a structural change in the brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased grey matter volume in the prefrontal cortex\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with chronic pain. In fact, chronic pain is often linked to decreased grey matter volume in certain brain regions, including the prefrontal cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced sensory processing in the thalamus\u003C/strong\u003E is not a characteristic change in chronic pain. The thalamus is involved in sensory processing, but chronic pain is more associated with changes in connectivity and processing in cortical regions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased activity in the amygdala\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically seen in chronic pain. The amygdala is involved in emotional processing, and chronic pain can lead to increased activity in this region due to the emotional distress associated with persistent pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic pain is associated with changes in brain structure and function, including altered connectivity between brain regions.","The insular cortex and frontal cortex are involved in the processing of pain and emotional responses.","Chronic pain can lead to increased emotional processing and altered connectivity between the frontal and insular cortex with subcortical structures."],"references":["May A. Chronic pain may change the structure of the brain. Pain. 2008 Jul;137(1):7-15. doi: 10.1016/j.pain.2008.02.034. Epub 2008 Apr 14. PMID: 18410991.","Rodriguez-Raecke R, Niemeier A, Ihle K, Ruether W, May A. Structural brain changes in chronic pain reflect probably neither damage nor atrophy. PLoS One. 2013;8(2):e54475. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0054475. Epub 2013 Feb 6. PMID: 23405082; PMCID: PMC3566164.","Yang S, Chang MC. Chronic Pain: Structural and Functional Changes in Brain Structures and Associated Negative Affective States. Int J Mol Sci. 2019 Jun 26;20(13):3130. doi: 10.3390/ijms20133130. PMID: 31248061; PMCID: PMC6650904.","Crofford LJ. Chronic Pain: Where the Body Meets the Brain. Trans Am Clin Climatol Assoc. 2015;126:167-83. PMID: 26330672; PMCID: PMC4530716."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57610"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17726"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57610"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T23:42:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T23:43:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10440"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72140"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedA